Scottish private schools still maintain their academic excellence, which was continued in 2018 with a string of commendable academic results, reinforced both individually and collectively in terms of sports, arts, music and community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, which are sponsored by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), are working to provide the best quality of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to equip deep and broad knowledge, as well as the career orientation and status of students as global citizens.
As an educational subdivision that can design and run the school’s distinctive curriculum, we see modern foreign languages continuing to be a popular and chosen topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to someone in the language he understands, what comes out will go into his mind.
If you talk to him in his own language, what he says will come into his heart.”
This is a convincing message that we don’t just rely on English when we want to establish relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From recent exams this year, we can see that foreign languages are leading the way in the rankings with the best pass scores in private schools.
A total of 68 percent of foreign language students scored higher than A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students scored more than an A in Chinese, while 72 percent learned German, 69 percent learned French and 63 percent learned Spanish also scored an A.
This suggests that private schools in Scotland are moving in the direction of treating foreign languages as essential skills that children and adolescents will not be able to lack in the future.
Elective foreign language subjects are being valued as STEM majors (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in programs at private schools as well as elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the British Council for Skills and Occupation in 2014 found that among the reasons employers have difficulty finding people, is due to a lack of foreign language skills.
As a result, foreign language skills are becoming more and more practical in order to equip young people for future career practice.
With more and more career prospects in need of a foreign language, these skills become practical in an increasingly flat world.
No matter how people choose to work, if they learn a second foreign language, they will gain a real advantage in the future when they have such a lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly in the native language of a native speaker, a multilingual person will obviously lead all trials.
According to a YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of them were unable to practice a simple assembly in another foreign language, and only French was the only foreign language with a percentage of units, 15 percent.
That’s why investing in teaching foreign languages is essential for children today.
Being in multilingual hands, especially those of developing economies, will equip children with a brighter potential to find a real job.
In Scotland, each school teaches different languages.
Some schools will focus on more modern foreign languages, while others will teach foreign languages that are considered important to the UK in the vision for 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
No matter what your child enjoys, there are a wide variety of foreign languages to choose from in private schools, along with a team of teachers with expertise in the profession.
Private schools in Scotland focus on providing an academic environment that prepares and equips children with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It is undeniable that, in an international business environment, foreign languages will continue to be extremely important factors for the future of the nation, which should be replicated in education.
In fact, modern foreign languages should be considered "international communication skills."
Private schools will continue to offer this opportunity to young Scots: diverse and outstanding.
