The National Trust listens to the secret lives of bats.
A new study is underway on land in the Scottish Highlands to reveal how bats use natural landscapes to hunt for food.
Hopefully these findings will shed light on the behavior of this unique flying mammal and orientation for future conservation activities.
The study, carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, tracked the journeys of popular bats, soprano pipistrelles, brown ears bats and Daubenton bats in the Inverewe Garden Area in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be located in key locations around the research site to monitor the activity of these bat species throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
The audio analyst will conduct an analysis of all sound recordings and determine the sound frequency of bat species and the purpose of playing the sound of each specific bat genus.
Subsequently, maps and reports of bat habitats will be created to take a detailed picture of the natural landscape of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes the results will help determine which habitats are most important to bats and how each species lives in that environment.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management activities of organisms, such as grassland cultivation and the best way to conserve forests for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect the bat’s bean truss and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting systems, fly trap paper, some chemical treatment methods for building materials, as well as pet cat attacks can also pose a risk to bats.
Bats are not completely blind.
However, due to the habit of hunting at night, the ears are more useful than the eyes when stalking and catching prey.
They use an extremely sophisticated echo positioning technique to identify obstacles on the flight path.
NTS is responsible for taking care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, while attaching special importance to bats.
The organization has ten trained professionals who regularly conduct surveys, checks and sometimes participate in animal rescue.
The organization even established Scotland’s first and only bat reserve at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway. It is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
Managing the land, David Thompson said the land was their ideal territory.
"Threave is a great habitat for bats," he said.
“We have a lot of old buildings, a lot of trees and a good living environment.
But there is still a lot of mystery about bats, so work here and in other facilities will help us better understand what bats need for further development.”
He stressed the importance of having to examine the lives of bats before conserving in the lands, because the accidental destruction of their breeding bean truss can kill up to 400 offspring and vomit offspring, almost completely destroying the population.
Bats are protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their bean truss.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an employee of the Scottish Bat Conservation Fund, encouraged the community to help.
“We still need to learn more about bats, and with many species, we can’t know how far apart their populations are.”
