Update on Red Tide: Reduced Red Tide Density in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Association shows that the density of the Red Tide has decreased in much of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, algae blooming has been reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – this causes red tide densities to decrease.
Red tides spread about 130 miles along the northern coast of Pinellas to south of Lee County.
Small plaques were also found within 10 miles off Hillsborough County, but fewer locations than last week.
Red tides were also observed in Pasco County.
Average density along the coast or offshore Pinellas County has been reported over the past week, low to high density offshore of Hillsborough County, low to high density in Manatee County, low to high density offshore in Sarasota County, low to high density Charlotte County, low to high density coastal or offshore in Lee County, and low to high density in Collier County.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Respiratory irritation has not been reported in northwestern Florida in the past week.
